<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09098e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09098e">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09098e"> 98(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Pella / Avignon / Cairo )</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Eusebius, l. iii. c. 5. Le Clerc, Hist. Ecclesiast. p. 605. During this occasional absence, the bishop and church of Pella still retained the title of Jerusalem. In the same manner, the Roman pontiffs resided seventy years at Avignon; and the patriarchs of Alexandria have long since transferred their episcopal seat to Cairo. <small> Edward Gibbon, <a name="EGDF2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGDF2"><cite title="source">Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire</cite></a> (ed. unknown) I, (Chapter XV) 438n3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Pella was the capital of ancient Macedonia under Philip II. </mm> </dd></dl>
